column281: I lost my job at age 57 and have not worked since as I am caring for my father who had a stroke; additional income would be very desirable. Having money earlier would be beneficial as I don't think I will live that long and my doctor agrees. Life is chaos and I would like to preserve as much of my savings as possible; having SS benefits early would help that. The government is likely to change entitlement programs and it would be good to get some benefit in the likelihood the program will change to my detriment. I am fearful about money and this would provide another safety net in case my DB pension bombs. The benefit would be higher for the remainder of my life if the program is not changed.

column281: I will receive more money from social security if I wait. I may not live to see any benefits if I don't get it when I can. I may not be in good enough health to enjoy it if I wait. If I get the money earlier and invest it wisely I might end up with more than if I waited. I would have to pay for medicare out of my own pocket instead of having it deducted from the social security I receive. At the time I actually made this decision, I calculated what was the break even age and it was in the 70s far to late for me to be sure I would be able to enjoy it. I have sufficient retirement income outside social security that I might as well get what I can early and enjoy it now. The amount of social security I get is so low that it doesn't make any sence to wait.

I wonder if they will address that later in this survey. I think I'll pull out my PERS paperwork and figure out how much my benefits would be from them at that various ages.   I also need to find out if I'll have anything coming from Motion Picture Health and Welfare.  Bud said he was going to check on that since he's looking into retiring soon.  Wonder if he's done that yet. I should just continue with survey and see what information they provide in the process before I go any further with this. Lets see, I'm actually elligible to retire now if I could afford to do so. What would be the benefit of retiring now? I'd have time to do all the projects I don't have time to do now I'd have more time to spend with family. I could spend lots of time in genealogy research I'd have time for travel. I really don't see it getting much better any time soon.  That means that I need to allow even more of a \cushion\".  My cost of living will being increasing I'm sure" I just bought a house and received new home owner discount.  That means I have to stay in the house and cannot move for at least another year and half.  I have to wait at least that long before I can retire. column281: Having already gone through this process, I understand the indication that waiting to full retirement age is better; however, I qualified under my deceased husband's benefits at the age of 63. For those individuals who are able to wait until full retirement age, the advantage is much greater. If an individual is able to combine a regular retirement and full SS benefits, it will be a financial blessing to them. I elected to retire from the Federal Gov. at age 63, knowing that I would also qualify for 100% of my late husband's SS and the combined income has served me well. Some people say that starting to draw on their benefits earlier just adds on to their regular retirement benfits and they will just draw for more years. I can see where there would be a benefit to drawing SS early, if your other income/assets are very small and it is needed to live on.

column281: I can't think of a single good reason for a healthy, self-employed person such as myself, to purposefully choose to receive retirement benefits early. I guess retiring early would be necessary for someone in a truly grueling occupation, such as stone mason. I guess that retiring early might be necessary for someone in ill health. Since I am self-employed, I am not actually anticipating retiring at all. I have not made a huge amount of money during my working life, so retiring as late as possible might enable me to actually get a reasonable amount of Social Security per month. Retiring is a terrible thing for physical and mental health. I'd rather put it off as long as possible.

column281: The longer I work, the more I am contributing to FICA, so the more the system works. For many people this is great. If I owned my own business I would probably be so involved that retirement would not be something I thought about. I already have the freedom to take a long vacation should I chose to do so. I make enough money to hire others to make repairs and modificat Right now to look at the chart and see only a minimal difference between full retirement at 66 of $1k and $1132 for age 70, you may have the foresight to realize that $132 extra per month will be needed just to make do. Right now, with no ss increase in 2 If I do not receive a pension from my state or a private company, I will need as much ss as I can possibly get, so I opt to work until I'm at least 70. I noticed that I was getting slower at my job, so opted to take early retirement at 62.  If my health is great, I can possibly get a less stressful job after retiring to supplement the small ss payment. On paper it looks good, and you budget around the small amount because you hate your job and want to get out of there, but in reality you'll be pitching pennies to survive. Having to worry about money is no fun in retirement. in order to retire early, however, I had to cash in my IRAs and 401K.  I could never read all the books or watch all the movies I wanted to when I worked, so retiring early while I still have my eyesight means I can enjoy those activities. The very worst thing I've ever heard about early retirement is that a couple, each receiving a small ss check got sick, had medical bills they could not pay (because Medicare does not cover too much), and one dies.
